        <weapon>Crossbow
                <damage>1, 6</damage>
                <fire_actions>2</fire_actions>
                <range>15</range>
                <hands>2</hands>
                <bulk>14</bulk>
                <cost>35</cost>
                <usage>1</usage>
                <description>Where the longbow was the weapon of the yeomanry, the</description>
                <description>crossbow could be used by anyone. Much like the firearm</description>
                <description>today, it leveled the military playing field between</description>
                <description>commoner and knight or other trained soldier. The</description>
                <description>larger crossbows were more powerful than the longbow,</description>
                <description>although (at least for hand-carried crossbows) the</description>
                <description>arrow (called a "bolt" or "quarrel") was much shorter</description>
                <description>and did not have the range of the longbow. Crossbows</description>
                <description>also could not be fired as rapidly. Lighter crossbows</description>
                <description>had to be pulled back and locked by hand, then aimed</description>
                <description>and fired. Larger crossbows had to be pulled back by</description>
                <description>foot as well as hand! Crossbows were more difficult</description>
                <description>than bows to protect from dampness as well.</description>
                <description>   </description>
                <description>Crossbows were developed throughout the world, from</description>
                <description>Europe to China and Japan, to Africa, Burma, and even</description>
                <description>the Pacific islands.</description>
                <description>   </description>
                <description>One advantage of crossbows is that they are easy to use</description>
                <description>as unmanned traps. Also, an assistant can double the</description>
                <description>rate of fire of a normal or heavy crossbow if the</description>
                <description>assistant is also skilled in the crossbow's use and two</description>
                <description>crossbows are available, by readying one crossbow while</description>
                <description>the shooter is firing the other.</description>
        </weapon>
